								<p class="newsHead">Breaking News: Supreme Court rules in favour of banks in bank charges ‘test case’</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Nov&nbsp;2009</p>
								<p><p>Whilst the OFT has power to assess the fairness of terms in consumer contracts under the Regulations, banks could avail themselves of the exemption set out in Regulation 6(2)(b) which states that the assessment of the fairness of a term in a contract ‘shall not relate . . . to the adequacy of the price or remuneration, as against the goods or services supplied in exchange’. This exclusion effectively provides that ‘value for money’ is not something which falls within the remit of ‘fairness’ under the Regulations.</p><p>In the Court of Appeal, the OFT successfully argued that bank charges fell outside the exemption of Regulation 6(2)(b) on the basis that the exemption applied only to the ‘core terms’ of the contract and not to ancillary terms such as charges for unauthorised overdrafts. In a unanimous judgment, the Supreme Court has overturned this decision in holding that charges for unauthorised overdrafts were part of the price paid by the customer for the banking services provided and so fell within the exemption. In particular, the charges were not concealed default charges designed to discourage customers from becoming overdrawn on their accounts. Rather, the charges were to be regarded as part of the price paid for the package of services which made up a current account. In a further positive for the banks, the Supreme Court held that, whilst interpretation of the European directive which the Regulations implemented was a question of European law, it was not necessary to refer the matter to the European Court of Justice. </p><p>The banking sector will obviously be relieved at this decision but a note of caution should be sounded for a number of reasons. Firstly, Lord Walker made it clear that the scope of the appeal was limited to the question of whether the OFT could challenge the charges as being excessive in relation to the services supplied in exchange i.e. the applicability of Regulation 6(2). The court did not have the task of deciding whether the system of charging current accounts was actually ‘fair’. Secondly, the Supreme Court has left open the possibility of the OFT challenging the fairness of the charges according to other criteria. Thirdly, the Supreme Court stated that it might be open to question whether it is fair to subsidise some customers whose accounts always remain in credit by levies on others who experienced events they did not foresee when they opened their accounts. Finally, Lord Walker commented that Parliament might wish to consider whether to confer the higher degree of consumer protection afforded in this area by the national laws of some other member states. </p><p>The full implications of this decision will now need to be considered by the banking and legal professions. Further updates will be provided as the matter unfolds. </p><p>For further information, please contact Neil Smith on 0844 571 6232 or email <a href="mailto:neil.smith@optimalegal.co.uk">neil.smith@optimalegal.co.uk</a> <br /></p><p /></p>
								
								
								<img src="../../content/cms/uploads/large/21433.jpg"  />
								
